            'final_result': '## Implied Price-to-Sales Multiples at Two Secondary-Market Price Points\n\n### 1. Inputs from the SpaceX S-1 (filed May 20, 2026)\n\n**FY2025 consolidated revenue (recast to include xAI and X Holdings under common-control accounting):**\n- Total: **$18,674 million** ($18.674 billion)\n  - Space (Launch): $4,086M\n  - Connectivity (Starlink): $11,387M\n  - AI (xAI + X): $3,201M\n\n**Post-split share count (Class A + Class B), as of May 1, 2026, after giving effect to the Class C Reclassification, the Preferred Conversion, and the 5-for-1 2026 Stock Split (effective May 4, 2026):**\n- Class A: 6,932,508,000\n- Class B: 5,602,790,410\n- **Total: 12,535,298,410 shares**\n\nThe S-1 explicitly states: *"Unless otherwise stated or the context otherwise requires, all share and per share information included in this prospectus have been retroactively adjusted to reflect the 2026 Stock Split."* This is the appropriate post-split share count to apply to the secondary-market per-share prices, which are quoted on the same post-split basis.\n\n### 2. Implied Equity Value at Each Price Point\n\n| Source | Price/Share | × Shares Outstanding | Implied Equity Value |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Forge Global (mid-April 2026) | $604.00 | 12,535,298,410 | **~$7.57 trillion** |\n| Nasdaq Private Market (May 19, 2026) | $117.87 | 12,535,298,410 | **~$1.48 trillion** |\n\nNote: The Forge $604 figure is widely cited as implying a ~$1.03 trillion valuation. Applying the S-1\'s post-split share count to $604 actually produces ~$7.57 trillion — roughly 7.3x the cited $1.03 trillion figure. This is itself a structural artifact of private secondary markets (discussed below): the $1.03 trillion figure was almost certainly derived on a **pre-split** share base (i.e., before the 5-for-1 split), so $604 × ~1.7 billion pre-split shares ≈ $1.03 trillion. On a consistent post-split basis, the Forge quote implies ~$7.6 trillion, while the NPM quote implies ~$1.48 trillion — a divergence of ~5.1x, consistent with the ~5.1x ratio between the two per-share prices ($604 / $117.87 = 5.12x).\n\n### 3. Implied Price-to-Sales (P/S) Multiples\n\nUsing FY2025 consolidated revenue of $18,674M:\n\n| Source | Implied Equity Value | ÷ FY2025 Revenue | Implied P/S |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Forge Global ($604, post-split basis) | ~$7,571B | $18.674B | **~405.4x** |\n| Nasdaq Private Market ($117.87) | ~$1,478B | $18.674B | **~79.1x** |\n| Forge ($604) on the cited $1.03T valuation (pre-split share base) | ~$1,030B | $18.674B | **~55.2x** |\n\n**Divergence:** On a consistent post-split share count, the Forge-implied multiple (~405x) is approximately **5.1x** the NPM-implied multiple (~79x). If one instead uses the headline $1.03T Forge valuation (which appears to be on a pre-split share base), the Forge P/S is ~55x — actually *below* the NPM-implied ~79x, illustrating how sensitive the comparison is to which share base is used.\n\n### 4. Structural Features of Private Secondary Markets That Explain a >5x Divergence\n\nPrivate secondary markets are not unified, continuous, price-discovery mechanisms. Several structural features explain why two reputable data providers can publish per-share prices that differ by more than 5x for the same company within a ~5-week window:\n\n1. **Fragmented, non-interoperable venues.** Forge Global, Nasdaq Private Market (Tape D®), Hiive, EquityZen, and Notice each operate separate matching platforms with their own order books. There is no consolidated tape; a trade on one venue is not visible to participants on another. Bid/ask spreads can be wide and stale.\n\n2. **Thin, episodic liquidity.** Volumes are tiny relative to the share base. A handful of matched trades — sometimes a single block — can set a platform\'s "last price" or "derived price" for weeks. With ~12.5 billion shares outstanding, even a few thousand shares transacting can move a published indicative price dramatically without reflecting broad consensus.\n\n3. **Different price-construction methodologies.** Providers weight matched trades, bids, asks, and tender-offer marks differently. Forge publishes a "derived" valuation that often blends secondary trades with company tender prices and model inputs; NPM\'s Tape D® produces an estimated price-per-share benchmark. Methodology differences alone can produce large gaps even from the same underlying activity.\n\n4. **Share-class and split-timing mismatches.** SpaceX has multiple classes (A, B, C, D) and executed a 5-for-1 split effective May 4, 2026 — between the Forge (mid-April) and NPM (May 19) quotes. A provider quoting on a pre-split basis versus a post-split basis will produce a 5x difference mechanically. This is almost certainly a major contributor to the apparent 5x gap: the Forge $604 figure aligns with a ~$1.03T valuation only on a pre-split share base, while NPM\'s $117.87 is consistent with a post-split quote.\n\n5. **Information asymmetry and restricted access.** Only accredited investors and approved employees can transact; financial disclosure is limited pre-S-1. Participants price on partial information, rumors of IPO timing/target valuations, and tender-offer marks rather than audited, current financials. Sentiment about a rumored $1.5T IPO target can inflate one venue\'s quotes while another remains anchored to the last company tender.\n\n6. **Right of first refusal (ROFR) and transfer restrictions.** Company-approved transfers, employee tender offers, and ROFR-exercised trades clear at company-set prices, while open secondary bids reflect speculative demand. The two streams rarely converge until a public listing forces price discovery.\n\n7. **No short-selling / no arbitrage.** Because shares cannot be shorted and cross-venue arbitrage is impractical (transfer restrictions, accreditation, settlement friction), mispricings between venues persist rather than being arbitraged away as they would be in public markets.\n\n### 5. What the Filing\'s Omission of a Price Range Prevents an Analyst from Resolving\n\nThe S-1 is a preliminary prospectus. The cover page leaves the initial public offering price per share blank, the number of shares being offered blank (the fee table registers 66,666,670 shares with proposed maximum aggregate offering prices escalating from $5.5T to $7.5T — a placeholder bonfide estimate, not a priced range), and the post-offering share counts blank. The capitalization table references "an initial public offering price of $[blank] per share … (the midpoint of the price range set forth on the cover of this prospectus)."\n\nBecause no price range is disclosed, an analyst **cannot resolve**:\n\n- **The IPO-implied valuation and therefore the IPO-implied P/S multiple.** Without a per-share offering price, one cannot compute the post-money equity value at which SpaceX will actually go public, and thus cannot anchor the secondary-market quotes to a primary-market reference point.\n- **Which secondary-market quote is "correct."** With no priced IPO range to serve as a tie-breaker, an analyst cannot determine whether Forge\'s $604 (or the cited $1.03T) or NPM\'s $117.87 better reflects market consensus. The filing provides no independent valuation anchor.\n- **The post-offering share count and dilution.** The cover page blanks for shares outstanding "immediately after this offering" depend on the offering size and any greenshoe exercise, which themselves depend on price. Without a price, the fully-diluted post-IPO share count — and thus any per-share-based valuation — is indeterminate.\n- **Reconciliation of pre-split vs. post-split secondary quotes.** Because the 5-for-1 split (May 4, 2026) falls between the two secondary quotes, and because the filing does not provide a priced IPO reference on a consistent post-split basis, an analyst cannot definitively determine whether the 5x gap is a genuine valuation disagreement or largely a split-basis artifact. The filing\'s retrospective post-split adjustment of its own share counts does not extend to third-party secondary quotes.\n- **Whether the secondary-market premium/discount to the IPO is reasonable.** A priced range would let an analyst measure the secondary-to-primary spread; without it, the secondary quotes float free of any disclosed fundamental anchor, and the >5x divergence remains unresolvable from the filing alone.\n\nIn short, the omission of a price range leaves the analyst unable to convert any of the divergent secondary-market per-share prices into a defensible, filing-anchored enterprise or equity valuation, and unable to adjudicate which venue\'s quote is closer to the company\'s own view of fair value.\n\n---\n\n### Summary Table\n\n| Metric | Forge ($604) | NPM ($117.87) | Ratio |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Per-share price | $604.00 | $117.87 | 5.12x |\n| Post-split shares (S-1, May 1, 2026) | 12,535,298,410 | 12,535,298,410 | — |\n| Implied equity value (post-split basis) | ~$7,571B | ~$1,478B | 5.12x |\n| FY2025 consolidated revenue (S-1) | $18.674B | $18.674B | — |\n| **Implied P/S (post-split basis)** | **~405.4x** | **~79.1x** | 5.12x |\n| Implied P/S (Forge on cited $1.03T, pre-split basis) | ~55.2x | — | — |\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026) — FY2025 consolidated revenue ($18,674M), post-split share counts as of May 1, 2026 (6,932,508,000 Class A + 5,602,790,410 Class B), 5-for-1 2026 Stock Split effective May 4, 2026, retrospective post-split adjustment language, and omitted price range on cover page"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.nasdaqprivatemarket.com/company/spacex",\n      "name": "Nasdaq Private Market — SpaceX company page (secondary-market pricing methodology and Tape D® benchmarking)"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://ts2.tech/en/spacex-valuation-on-25-november-2025-private-markets-now-price-elon-musks-spacex-near-500-billion",\n      "name": "TS2 — SpaceX private-market valuation history (Forge per-share pricing and derived valuations, illustrating pre-split share-base conventions)"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.bitget.com/wiki/how-much-is-spacex-stock-worth",\n      "name": "Bitget — Overview of secondary-market providers (Forge, NPM, Hiive, EquityZen, Notice) and methodology differences"\n    }\n  ]\n}'
